The two basic concepts of calculus

A useful way to motivate calculus is to start from two closely related geometric questions. First, given a curve $y=f(x)$ drawn above a horizontal baseline and an interval $[a,b]$, we want to associate a single number with the region bounded by the curve, the baseline, and the vertical lines $x=a$ and $x=b$. This motivates the notion of area and leads naturally to the idea of an integral. Second, given a point $x=c$ on the same curve, we want to associate a single number with the steepness of the tangent line at that point. This motivates the notion of instantaneous rate of change and leads to the idea of a derivative. In the formal development, these two measurementsarea and steepnessbecome the organizing problems around which integral and differential calculus are built (Adapted from the motivating discussion in Apostol, Calculus, Vol. 1, 2nd ed., p. 2.).

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Core functions
# ------------------------------------------------------------
def f_curve(x, A=0.9, w=1.0, phi=0.0, shift=1.6):
    """Upward-shifted sine curve."""
    return shift + A * np.sin(w * x + phi)


def deriv_central(f, x0, h=1e-4):
    """Central-difference derivative approximation."""
    return (f(x0 + h) - f(x0 - h)) / (2 * h)


def clamp(x, lo, hi):
    return lo if x < lo else hi if x > hi else x


def trapz_area(y, x):
    """Trapezoidal integration with NumPy-version fallback."""
    if hasattr(np, "trapezoid"):
        return np.trapezoid(y, x)
    return np.trapz(y, x)


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Plotting
# ------------------------------------------------------------
def render(
    A=0.9, w=1.0, phi=0.0, shift=1.6,
    a=1.0, b=6.0, c=7.2,
    xmin=0.0, xmax=10.0,
    fig_path="assets/figures/figure1.png"
):
    # Normalize intervals
    a_, b_ = (a, b) if a <= b else (b, a)
    a_ = clamp(a_, xmin, xmax)
    b_ = clamp(b_, xmin, xmax)
    c_ = clamp(c, xmin, xmax)

    # Sampling for curve
    N = 2500
    x = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, N)

    f = lambda t: f_curve(t, A=A, w=w, phi=phi, shift=shift)
    y = f(x)

    # Area on [a,b]
    x_area = np.linspace(a_, b_, 8000)  # 15000 -> 8000 (lighter, still smooth)
    area = trapz_area(f(x_area), x_area)

    # Tangent at c
    m = deriv_central(f, c_)
    yc = f(c_)
    tangent = yc + m * (x - c_)

    with out:
        clear_output(wait=True)

        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12.5, 8.0), dpi=150)

        # Minimal axis styling
        for s in ["top", "right", "bottom", "left"]:
            ax.spines[s].set_visible(False)
        ax.set_xticks([])
        ax.set_yticks([])

        # Axis arrows
        y_top = float(max(np.max(y), 0.0) * 1.12)
        ax.annotate("", xy=(xmax, 0), xytext=(xmin, 0),
                    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", lw=1.9))
        ax.annotate("", xy=(0, y_top), xytext=(0, 0),
                    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", lw=1.9))

        ax.text(xmax, -0.20, r"$x$", ha="right", va="top", fontsize=26)
        ax.text(-0.20, y_top, r"$y$", ha="right", va="bottom", fontsize=26)

        # Curve
        ax.plot(x, y, lw=3.2)
        xC = xmin + 0.48 * (xmax - xmin)
        ax.text(xC, float(f(xC)) + 0.20, r"$C$", fontsize=28)

        # Shaded area
        mask = (x >= a_) & (x <= b_)
        ax.fill_between(x[mask], 0, y[mask], alpha=0.18)
        ax.vlines([a_, b_], [0, 0], [float(f(a_)), float(f(b_))], lw=2.2)

        # Tangent line
        ax.plot(x, tangent, lw=2.6)

        # Tangent label
        x_lab = clamp(c_ + 0.9, xmin + 0.5, xmax - 1.2)
        y_lab = yc + m * (x_lab - c_)
        ax.text(x_lab, y_lab + 0.18, "Line tangent to $C$", fontsize=18, ha="left")

        # Tangency point + direction arrow
        ax.scatter([c_], [yc], s=90, zorder=3)
        dx = 0.9
        ax.annotate("", xy=(c_ + dx, yc + m * dx), xytext=(c_, yc),
                    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", lw=1.7))
        ax.text(c_ + dx + 0.18, yc + m * dx + 0.04, "steepness", fontsize=18)

        # Labels for a, b, c
        ax.text(a_, -0.34, r"$a$", ha="center", va="top", fontsize=24)
        ax.text(b_, -0.34, r"$b$", ha="center", va="top", fontsize=24)
        ax.text(c_, -0.34, r"$c$", ha="center", va="top", fontsize=24)

        ax.set_xlim(xmin, xmax)
        ax.set_ylim(-0.60, float(max(np.max(y), 0.0) * 1.18))

        # Info box
        info = (
            r"$A(a,b)\approx \int_a^b f(x)\,dx \approx$ " + f"{area:.4f}\n"
            r"$m(c)\approx f'(c)\approx$ " + f"{m:.4f}\n\n"
            "Apostol, Calculus Vol. 1 (2nd ed.), p. 2"
        )
        ax.text(0.06, 0.92, info, transform=ax.transAxes,
                ha="left", va="top", fontsize=17,
                bbox=dict(boxstyle="round,pad=0.55", fc="0.98", ec="0.35", lw=1.0))

        # Caption
        caption = (
            "Figure 1. Two basic measurements: "
            r"$A(a,b)=\int_a^b f(x)\,dx$ and $m(c)=f'(c)$. "
            "Apostol (Vol. 1, 2nd ed.), p. 2."
        )
        fig.subplots_adjust(bottom=0.20)
        fig.text(0.07, 0.04, caption, fontsize=18)

        # Save (safe)
        if fig_path:
            folder = os.path.dirname(fig_path)
            if folder:
                os.makedirs(folder, exist_ok=True)
            fig.savefig(fig_path, dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")

        plt.show()

        # Table
        df = pd.DataFrame({
            "Parameter": [
                "A (amplitude)", "w (frequency)", "phi (phase)", "shift",
                "a", "b", "c",
                "Area  A(a,b)", "Slope m(c)"
            ],
            "Value": [
                A, w, phi, shift,
                a_, b_, c_,
                area, m
            ]
        })
        df["Value"] = df["Value"].astype(float).round(6)
        display(df)

Historical background

Calculus, at its core, is concerned with the precise formulation and solution of two fundamental geometric measurement problems: the assignment of a number to represent the area of a region and the assignment of a number to represent the steepness of a tangent line at a point on a curve. In modern language, these two measurements are expressed by the integral and the derivative, which allow us to define the concepts of area and tangent line and to compute, respectively, the area of a given region and the slope of a given tangent. The historical origin of integral calculus goes back more than two thousand years to the Greek method of exhaustion, in which one approximates a given region by inscribed polygonal regions whose areas can be computed exactly, then improves the approximation by using polygons with more and more sides in an attempt to exhaust the region. This idea was used with remarkable success by Archimedes to obtain exact formulas for the area of the circle and other special figures, but further development was impossible at the time due to the absence of a suitable algebraic language. The elementary algebra familiar today did not exist in antiquity, and without efficient symbolic notation it was practically impossible to extend the method to general classes of regions. A slow but revolutionary transformation began in the sixteenth century with the replacement of Roman numerals by HinduArabic numerals, the introduction of the symbols + and , and the growing acceptance of decimal notation; during the same period, the work of Tartaglia, Cardano, and Ferrari on cubic and quartic equations greatly advanced algebraic methods and encouraged the adoption of a more powerful symbolic language. With the widespread use of well-chosen algebraic symbols, interest in the ancient method of exhaustion was revived, leading to many partial results by Cavalieri, Torricelli, Roberval, Fermat, Pascal, and Wallis, and gradually the method evolved into what is now called integral calculus, a new and powerful discipline with applications far beyond geometry. Its greatest impetus came in the seventeenth century through the work of Isaac Newton and Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, and its rigorous foundations were established in the nineteenth century by mathematicians such as Augustin-Louis Cauchy and Bernhard Riemann, while further refinements and extensions of the theory continue in contemporary mathematics.

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Geometry: upper semicircle (center at 0,0)
# ------------------------------------------------------------
def y_semicircle(x, R=1.0):
    return np.sqrt(np.clip(R * R - x * x, 0.0, None))

def poly_area_under_polyline(xs, ys):
    dx = np.diff(xs)
    return np.sum(dx * (ys[:-1] + ys[1:]) / 2.0)

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Render
# ------------------------------------------------------------
def render_exhaustion(
    n=6,
    R=1.0,
    show_trapezoids=True,
    xmin=-1.25,
    xmax=1.25,
    fig_path=None
):
    n = int(max(2, n))
    R = float(max(0.1, R))

    xs = np.linspace(-R, R, n + 1)
    ys = y_semicircle(xs, R=R)

    true_area = 0.5 * np.pi * R * R
    approx_area = poly_area_under_polyline(xs, ys)

    err = approx_area - true_area
    rel = err / true_area if true_area != 0 else 0.0
    rel_pct = f"{rel*100:+.4f}%"

    with out:
        clear_output(wait=True)

        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12.5, 7.6), dpi=150)

        for s in ["top", "right", "bottom", "left"]:
            ax.spines[s].set_visible(False)
        ax.set_xticks([])
        ax.set_yticks([])

        # Axis arrows
        ax.annotate("", xy=(xmax, 0), xytext=(xmin, 0),
                    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", lw=1.9))
        ax.annotate("", xy=(0, 1.15 * R), xytext=(0, -0.05 * R),
                    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", lw=1.9))
        ax.text(xmax, -0.10 * R, r"$x$", ha="right", va="top", fontsize=26)
        ax.text(-0.08 * R, 1.15 * R, r"$y$", ha="right", va="bottom", fontsize=26)

        # True semicircle arc
        xfine = np.linspace(-R, R, 1200)
        yfine = y_semicircle(xfine, R=R)
        ax.plot(xfine, yfine, lw=3.2)

        # Polygonal approximation
        ax.plot(xs, ys, lw=2.6)

        # Shaded approximate area
        ax.fill_between(xs, 0, ys, alpha=0.18)

        if show_trapezoids:
            for i in range(n):
                xa, xb = xs[i], xs[i + 1]
                ya, yb = ys[i], ys[i + 1]
                ax.vlines([xa, xb], [0, 0], [ya, yb], lw=1.1, alpha=0.9)

        ax.text(0.60 * R, 0.62 * R, r"$C$", fontsize=30)

        # Info box
        box = (
            rf"$n={n}$ piecewise approximation" + "\n"
            + rf"$A_n \approx {approx_area:.6f}$" + "\n"
            + rf"$A = \frac{{\pi R^2}}{{2}} = {true_area:.6f}$" + "\n"
            + rf"Error $A_n-A \approx {err:+.6f}$" + "\n"
            + f"Relative error  {rel_pct}"
        )
        ax.text(0.05, 0.93, box, transform=ax.transAxes,
                ha="left", va="top", fontsize=17,
                bbox=dict(boxstyle="round,pad=0.55", fc="0.98", ec="0.35", lw=1.0))

        caption = (
            "Method of exhaustion (semicircle): piecewise-linear approximation under the arc; "
            "as $n$ increases, $A_n \\to \\pi R^2/2$."
        )
        fig.subplots_adjust(bottom=0.18)
        fig.text(0.07, 0.04, caption, fontsize=18)

        ax.set_xlim(xmin, xmax)
        ax.set_ylim(-0.20 * R, 1.25 * R)

        # Save (safe)
        if fig_path:
            folder = os.path.dirname(fig_path)
            if folder:
                os.makedirs(folder, exist_ok=True)
            fig.savefig(fig_path, dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")

        plt.show()

        # Table + caption
        df = pd.DataFrame({
            "Metric": ["n", "R", "Approx area (A_n)", "True area (R/2)", "Error (A_n - A)", "Relative error"],
            "Value": [n, R, approx_area, true_area, err, rel],
        })

        table_caption = (
            f"**Figure 2:** Metrics for the semicircle of radius $R={R:.2f}$ using a "
            f"piecewise-linear approximation with $n={n}$ subintervals."
        )

        display(Markdown(table_caption))
        display(df)

The method of exhaustion for the area of a parabolic segment

For the sake of simplicity, we subdivide the base into $n$ equal parts, each of length

$$ \frac{b}{n}. $$

The points of subdivision correspond to the following values of $x$:

$$ 0, \frac{b}{n}, \frac{2b}{n}, \frac{3b}{n}, \dots, \frac{(n-1)b}{n}, \frac{nb}{n} = b. $$

A typical point of subdivision corresponds to

$$ x = \frac{k b}{n}, $$

where $k$ takes the successive values

$$ k = 0,1,2,3,\dots,n. $$

At each point

$$ \frac{k b}{n} $$

we construct the outer rectangle of altitude

$$ \left( \frac{k b}{n} \right)^2 $$

as illustrated in Figure 3. The area of this rectangle is the product of its base and its altitude and is equal to

$$ \frac{b}{n} \cdot \left( \frac{k b}{n} \right)^2 = \frac{b^3}{n^3} k^2. $$

Let us denote by $S_n$ the sum of the areas of all the outer rectangles. Since the $k$-th rectangle has area

$$ \frac{b^3}{n^3} k^2, $$

we obtain the formula

$$ S_n = \frac{b^3}{n^3} \left( 1^2 + 2^2 + 3^2 + \cdots + n^2 \right). \tag{1.1} $$

In the same way we obtain a formula for the sum $s_n$ of all the inner rectangles:

$$ s_n = \frac{b^3}{n^3} \left( 1^2 + 2^2 + 3^2 + \cdots + (n-1)^2 \right). \tag{1.2} $$

This brings us to a very important stage in the calculation. Notice that the factor multiplying

$$ \frac{b^3}{n^3} $$

in equation (1.1) is the sum of the squares of the first $n$ integers:

$$ 1^2 + 2^2 + \cdots + n^2. $$

The corresponding factor in equation (1.2) is similar, except that the sum has only $n-1$ terms. For large values of $n$, the computation of this sum by direct addition is tedious and inconvenient. Fortunately, there is an interesting identity which makes it possible to evaluate this sum in a simpler way, namely,

$$ 1^2 + 2^2 + \cdots + n^2 = \frac{n^3}{3} + \frac{n^2}{2} + \frac{n}{6}. \tag{1.3} $$

This identity is valid for every integer

$$ n \ge 1 $$

and can be proved as follows. Start with the formula

$$ (k+1)^3 = k^3 + 3k^2 + 3k + 1. $$

This may be rewritten in the form

$$ 3k^2 + 3k + 1 = (k+1)^3 - k^3, \quad k = 1,2,\dots,n-1. $$

Thus we obtain the identities

$$ 3\cdot1^2 + 3\cdot1 + 1 = 2^3 - 1^3, $$

$$ 3\cdot2^2 + 3\cdot2 + 1 = 3^3 - 2^3, $$

$$ \vdots $$

$$ 3(n-1)^2 + 3(n-1) + 1 = n^3 - (n-1)^3. $$

When we add these formulas, all the terms on the right cancel except two, and we obtain

$$ 3[1^2 + 2^2 + \cdots + (n-1)^2] + 3[1 + 2 + \cdots + (n-1)] + (n-1) = n^3 - 1^3. $$

The second sum on the left is the sum of an arithmetic progression and simplifies to

$$ \frac{1}{2} n (n-1). $$

Hence we obtain

$$ 1^2 + 2^2 + \cdots + (n-1)^2 = \frac{n^3}{3} - \frac{n^2}{2} + \frac{n}{6}. \tag{1.4} $$

Adding $n^2$ to both members, we recover equation (1.3). For our purposes, we do not need the exact expressions given in (1.3) and (1.4). All we need are the inequalities

$$ 1^2 + 2^2 + \cdots + (n-1)^2 < \frac{n^3}{3} < 1^2 + 2^2 + \cdots + n^2. \tag{1.5} $$

These inequalities are valid for every integer

$$ n \ge 1. $$

If we multiply both sides of (1.5) by

$$ \frac{b^3}{n^3} $$

and use (1.1) and (1.2), we obtain

$$ s_n < \frac{b^3}{3} < S_n. \tag{1.6} $$

The inequalities in (1.6) show that

$$ \frac{b^3}{3} $$

is the only number with this property. That is, if $A$ is any number such that

$$ s_n < A < S_n \tag{1.7} $$

for every positive integer $n$, then

$$ A = \frac{b^3}{3}. $$

This is the reason Archimedes concluded that the area of the parabolic segment is

$$ \frac{b^3}{3}. $$

To prove this rigorously, we use the inequalities in (1.5) once more. Adding $n^2$ to both sides of the left inequality in (1.5), we obtain

$$ 1^2 + 2^2 + \cdots + n^2 < \frac{n^3}{3} + n^2. $$

Multiplying by

$$ \frac{b^3}{n^3} $$

and using (1.1), we get

$$ S_n < \frac{b^3}{3} + \frac{b^3}{n}. \tag{1.8} $$

Similarly, subtracting $n^2$ from both sides of the right inequality in (1.5) and multiplying by

$$ \frac{b^3}{n^3} $$

we obtain

$$ \frac{b^3}{3} - \frac{b^3}{n} < s_n. \tag{1.9} $$

Therefore, any number $A$ satisfying (1.7) must also satisfy

$$ \frac{b^3}{3} - \frac{b^3}{n} < A < \frac{b^3}{3} + \frac{b^3}{n}. \tag{1.10} $$

for every integer

$$ n \ge 1. $$

Now there are only three possibilities:

$$ A > \frac{b^3}{3}, \quad A < \frac{b^3}{3}, \quad A = \frac{b^3}{3}. $$

If we show that the first two lead to contradictions, then we must have

$$ A = \frac{b^3}{3}. $$

Suppose first that

$$ A > \frac{b^3}{3}. $$

From the second inequality in (1.10) we obtain

$$ A - \frac{b^3}{3} < \frac{b^3}{n}. \tag{1.11} $$

Since

$$ A - \frac{b^3}{3} > 0, $$

we may divide both sides by this quantity and multiply by $n$, obtaining

$$ n < \frac{b^3}{A - b^3/3}. $$

But this inequality is false for sufficiently large $n$. Hence the assumption

$$ A > \frac{b^3}{3} $$

leads to a contradiction. A similar argument shows that

$$ A < \frac{b^3}{3} $$

also leads to a contradiction. Therefore we must have

$$ \boxed{A = \frac{b^3}{3}}. $$

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Style
# ------------------------------------------------------------
plt.rcParams.update({
    "font.family": "STIXGeneral",
    "mathtext.fontset": "stix",
    "font.size": 22,
})

out = Output()

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Core math
# ------------------------------------------------------------
def f_parabola(x):
    return x * x

def clamp(x, lo, hi):
    return lo if x < lo else hi if x > hi else x

def sum_squares(n):
    # 1^2 + ... + n^2
    n = int(n)
    return n * (n + 1) * (2 * n + 1) / 6

def inner_sum_area(b, n):
    # inner: k=0..n-1, height f(kb/n)
    # area = (b/n) * sum_{k=0}^{n-1} (kb/n)^2 = (b^3/n^3) * sum_{k=0}^{n-1} k^2
    return (b**3 / n**3) * sum_squares(n - 1)

def outer_sum_area(b, n):
    # outer: k=1..n, height f(kb/n)
    # area = (b^3/n^3) * sum_{k=1}^{n} k^2
    return (b**3 / n**3) * sum_squares(n)

def true_area(b):
    # Integral_0^b x^2 dx = b^3/3
    return b**3 / 3.0

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Rendering
# ------------------------------------------------------------
def render_archimedes(
    n=6,
    b=1.0,
    show_dividers=True,
    xmin=-0.08,
    xmax=1.10,
    fig_path="assets/figures/figure3.png"
):
    n = int(max(2, n))
    b = float(max(0.1, b))

    # curve sampling
    xs = np.linspace(0.0, b, 1400)
    ys = f_parabola(xs)

    # partition points
    xk = np.linspace(0.0, b, n + 1)
    yk = f_parabola(xk)

    # areas
    s_n = inner_sum_area(b, n)
    S_n = outer_sum_area(b, n)
    A = true_area(b)

    err_inner = s_n - A
    err_outer = S_n - A

    with out:
        clear_output(wait=True)

        fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15.0, 6.0), dpi=150)

        # ---------- common axis styling ----------
        for ax in axs:
            for s in ["top", "right", "bottom", "left"]:
                ax.spines[s].set_visible(False)
            ax.set_xticks([])
            ax.set_yticks([])

        # axis limits
        y_top = float((b*b) * 1.10)
        x_left = xmin * b
        x_right = xmax * b

        # ---------- Figure 3a (inner rectangles) ----------
        ax = axs[0]

        # axis arrows
        ax.annotate("", xy=(x_right, 0), xytext=(x_left, 0),
                    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", lw=1.9))

        ax.text(-0.06*b, y_top, r"$y$", ha="right", va="bottom", fontsize=26)

        # curve
        ax.plot(xs, ys, lw=3.2)

Exercise 1: Scaling / shifting the ordinate in Figure 1.3 (parabolic segment)

We replace the ordinate function in Figure 1.3 by a more general quadratic form

$$ y(x)=\alpha x^2+\beta \qquad (0\le x\le b). $$

Special cases in the exercise:

  • $$2x^2 \Rightarrow \alpha=2,\ \beta=0$$
  • $$3x^2 \Rightarrow \alpha=3,\ \beta=0$$
  • $$\frac{1}{2}x^2 \Rightarrow \alpha=\frac{1}{2},\ \beta=0$$
  • $$2x^2+1 \Rightarrow \alpha=2,\ \beta=1$$
  • $$ax^2+c \Rightarrow \alpha=a,\ \beta=c$$

Exact area under the curve on $[0,b]$ is

$$ A=\int_0^b (\alpha x^2+\beta)\,dx = \alpha\frac{b^3}{3}+\beta b. $$

To mirror the method of exhaustion idea, we approximate the area with:

  • inner sum using left-endpoint rectangles,
  • outer sum using right-endpoint rectangles,

then watch how both squeeze the true value as $n$ increases.

# Style

plt.rcParams.update({
    "font.family": "STIXGeneral",
    "mathtext.fontset": "stix",
    "font.size": 22,

out = Output()

def y_quad(x, alpha=1.0, beta=0.0):
    return alpha * x * x + beta

def clamp(x, lo, hi):
    return lo if x < lo else hi if x > hi else x

def rect_sums(alpha, beta, b, n):
    """
    Inner (left) and outer (right) rectangle sums on [0,b] for y=alpha x^2 + beta.
    """
    n = int(max(1, n))
    b = float(max(1e-9, b))
    dx = b / n

    # partition points: x_k = k dx
    xs = np.linspace(0.0, b, n + 1)

    # inner uses left endpoints: k=0..n-1
    xL = xs[:-1]
    # outer uses right endpoints: k=1..n
    xR = xs[1:]

    inner = dx * np.sum(y_quad(xL, alpha, beta))
    outer = dx * np.sum(y_quad(xR, alpha, beta))

    return inner, outer, dx, xs, xL, xR

def exact_area(alpha, beta, b):
    return alpha * (b**3) / 3.0 + beta * b

def render_ex1(alpha=2.0, beta=0.0, b=1.0, n=6, show_inner=True, show_outer=True):
    alpha = float(alpha)
    beta  = float(beta)
    b     = float(max(0.2, b))
    n     = int(max(1, n))

    inner, outer, dx, xs, xL, xR = rect_sums(alpha, beta, b, n)
    A = exact_area(alpha, beta, b)

    with out:
        clear_output(wait=True)

        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12.5, 7.6), dpi=150)

        # Minimal axes
        for s in ["top", "right", "bottom", "left"]:
            ax.spines[s].set_visible(False)
        ax.set_xticks([])
        ax.set_yticks([])

        # Plot range
        xmin, xmax = -0.05*b, 1.15*b
        xfine = np.linspace(0.0, b, 1200)
        yfine = y_quad(xfine, alpha, beta)
        ymax = float(max(np.max(yfine), beta) * 1.15 + 0.15)

        # Axis arrows
        ax.annotate("", xy=(xmax, 0), xytext=(xmin, 0),
                    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", lw=1.9))
        ax.annotate("", xy=(0, ymax), xytext=(0, 0),
                    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", lw=1.9))
        ax.text(xmax, -0.08*ymax, r"$x$", ha="right", va="top", fontsize=26)
        ax.text(-0.03*b, ymax, r"$y$", ha="right", va="bottom", fontsize=26)

        # Curve
        ax.plot(xfine, yfine, lw=3.2)
        ax.text(0.72*b, y_quad(0.72*b, alpha, beta) + 0.08*ymax, r"$C$", fontsize=30)

        # Draw rectangles (inner / outer)
        # inner rectangles: height at left endpoints
        if show_inner:
            for k in range(n):

        # outer rectangles: height at right endpoints
        if show_outer:

        ax.text(0.0, -0.10*ymax, r"$0$", ha="center", va="top", fontsize=22)

        # Info box (avoid LaTeX-percent pitfalls)
        gap_in = A - inner

        ax.text(0.05, 0.94, box, transform=ax.transAxes,

        caption = (
            "Exercise 1: inner/outer rectangles for $y(x)=\\alpha x^2+\\beta$ on $[0,b]$."
        )
        fig.subplots_adjust(bottom=0.18)
        fig.text(0.07, 0.04, caption, fontsize=18)

Exercise 2: Replace $x^2$ by $x^3$ (and recover $b^4/4$)

Now we take

$$ y(x)=x^3 \qquad (0\le x\le b). $$

Using the same partition $x_k=\frac{k b}{n}$ with $\Delta x=\frac{b}{n}$:

  • Outer rectangles (right endpoints) have total area

$$ S_n=\frac{b^4}{n^4}\left(1^3+2^3+\cdots+n^3\right). $$

  • Inner rectangles (left endpoints) have total area

$$ s_n=\frac{b^4}{n^4}\left(1^3+2^3+\cdots+(n-1)^3\right). $$

Since the exact area is

$$ A=\int_0^b x^3\,dx=\frac{b^4}{4}, $$

we can see numerically (and visually) that

$$ s_n<\frac{b^4}{4}<S_n $$

and the squeeze improves as $n$ increases.

Exercise 3: General power $k$ (the $n^{k+1}/(k+1)$ squeeze)

Assume the general inequality (given in the text) for integers $n\ge 1$ and $k\ge 1$:

$$ 1^k+2^k+\cdots+(n-1)^k < \frac{n^{k+1}}{k+1} < 1^k+2^k+\cdots+n^k. $$

If we take

$$ y(x)=x^k \qquad (0\le x\le b), $$

and use the same partition $$x_j=\frac{jb}{n}$$, then the rectangle sums become

$$ s_n=\frac{b^{k+1}}{n^{k+1}}\left(1^k+2^k+\cdots+(n-1)^k\right), $$

$$ S_n=\frac{b^{k+1}}{n^{k+1}}\left(1^k+2^k+\cdots+n^k\right), $$

and the exact area is

$$ A=\int_0^b x^k\,dx=\frac{b^{k+1}}{k+1}. $$

So the same squeeze picture works for every $k\ge 1$.

In[8]:

    "mathtext.fontset": "stix",
    "font.size": 22,

out3 = Output()

def y_power(x, k):
    return x**k

def sums_power(b, n, k):
    n = int(max(1, n))
    b = float(max(1e-9, b))
    k = int(max(1, k))
    dx = b / n
    xs = np.linspace(0.0, b, n + 1)
    xL = xs[:-1]
    xR = xs[1:]
    s_n = dx * np.sum(y_power(xL, k))
    S_n = dx * np.sum(y_power(xR, k))
    A = b**(k+1) / (k+1)
    return s_n, S_n, A, dx, xs

def render_ex3(b=1.0, n=10, k=3, show_inner=True, show_outer=True):
    b = float(max(0.2, b))
    n = int(max(1, n))
    k = int(max(1, k))

    s_n, S_n, A, dx, xs = sums_power(b, n, k)

    with out3:
        clear_output(wait=True)

        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12.5, 7.6), dpi=150)

        for s in ["top", "right", "bottom", "left"]:
            ax.spines[s].set_visible(False)
        ax.set_xticks([])
        ax.set_yticks([])

        xmin, xmax = -0.05*b, 1.15*b
        xfine = np.linspace(0.0, b, 1200)
        yfine = y_power(xfine, k)
        ymax = float(np.max(yfine) * 1.15 + 0.15)

        ax.annotate("", xy=(xmax, 0), xytext=(xmin, 0),
                    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", lw=1.9))
        ax.annotate("", xy=(0, ymax), xytext=(0, 0),
                    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", lw=1.9))
        ax.text(xmax, -0.08*ymax, r"$x$", ha="right", va="top", fontsize=26)
        ax.text(-0.03*b, ymax, r"$y$", ha="right", va="bottom", fontsize=26)

        ax.plot(xfine, yfine, lw=3.2)
        ax.text(0.72*b, y_power(0.72*b, k) + 0.08*ymax, r"$C$", fontsize=30)

        if show_inner:
            for j in range(n):
                x0 = xs[j]
                h  = y_power(x0, k)
                ax.add_patch(plt.Rectangle((x0, 0), dx, h, fill=True, alpha=0.16, ec="0.2", lw=0.8))
        if show_outer:
            for j in range(1, n+1):
                x0 = xs[j-1]
                h  = y_power(xs[j], k)
                ax.add_patch(plt.Rectangle((x0, 0), dx, h, fill=True, alpha=0.10, ec="0.2", lw=0.8))

        gap_in  = A - s_n
        gap_out = S_n - A

        box = (
            rf"$y(x)=x^k$ with $k={k}$ on $[0,b]$" + "\n"
            + rf"$b={b:.3g}$, $n={n}$, $\Delta x=b/n={dx:.4f}$" + "\n\n"
            + rf"$s_n \approx {s_n:.6f}$" + "\n"
            + rf"$S_n \approx {S_n:.6f}$" + "\n"
            + rf"$A=\frac{{b^{{k+1}}}}{{k+1}} \approx {A:.6f}$" + "\n\n"
            + f"$A-s_n \\approx {gap_in:+.6f}$,  $S_n-A \\approx {gap_out:+.6f}$"
        )
        ax.text(0.05, 0.94, box, transform=ax.transAxes,
                ha="left", va="top", fontsize=17,
                bbox=dict(boxstyle="round,pad=0.55", fc="0.98", ec="0.35", lw=1.0))

        caption = "Exercise 3: same squeeze for $y=x^k$; limit is $b^{k+1}/(k+1)$."
        fig.subplots_adjust(bottom=0.18)
        fig.text(0.07, 0.04, caption, fontsize=18)

        ax.set_xlim(xmin, xmax)
        ax.set_ylim(-0.14*ymax, ymax)

        plt.show()

        df = pd.DataFrame({
            "Metric": ["k", "b", "n", "dx", "inner s_n", "outer S_n", "exact A=b^(k+1)/(k+1)"],
            "Value": [k, b, n, dx, s_n, S_n, A]
        })
        display(df.round(6))
